SIMPLE: wink
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wink
<hw>Wink</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Winked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Winking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>winken</ets>, AS.
<ets>wincian</ets>; akin to D. <ets>wenken</ets>, G. <ets>winken</ets>
to wink, nod, beckon, OHG. <ets>winchan</ets>, Sw. <ets>vinka</ets>,
Dan. <ets>vinke</ets>, AS. <ets>wancol</ets> wavering, OHG.
<ets>wanchal</ets> wavering, <ets>wanch<?/n</ets> to waver, G.
<ets>wanken</ets>, and perhaps to E. <ets>weak</ets>; cf. AS.
<ets>wincel</ets> a corner. Cf. <er>Wench</er>, <er>Wince</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To nod; to sleep; to nap.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Although I wake or <xex>wink</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shut the eyes quickly; to close the eyelids with
a quick motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He must <qex>wink</qex>, so loud he would cry.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And I will <qex>wink</qex>, so shall the day seem night.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are not blind, but they <qex>wink</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To close and open the eyelids quickly; to nictitate;
to blink.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A baby of some three months old, who <qex>winked</qex>, and turned
aside its little face from the too vivid light of day.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give a hint by a motion of the eyelids, often
those of one eye only.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wink</qex> at the footman to leave him without a plate.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To avoid taking notice, as if by shutting the eyes;
to connive at anything; to be tolerant; -- generally with
<xex>at</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The times of this ignorance God <qex>winked at</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xvii. 30.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And yet, as though he knew it not,⟦br⟧
His knowledge <qex>winks</qex>, and lets his humors reign.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Obstinacy can not be <qex>winked</qex> at, but must be
subdued.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To be dim and flicker; <as>as, the light
<ex>winks</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Winking monkey</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
white-nosed monkey (<spn>Cersopithecus nictitans</spn>).</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wink
<hw>Wink</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To cause (the eyes) to
wink.</def><mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wink</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wink
<hw>Wink</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of closing, or
closing and opening, the eyelids quickly; hence, the time necessary for
such an act; a moment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have not slept one <qex>wink</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I could eclipse and cloud them with a <qex>wink</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Donne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A hint given by shutting the eye with a significant
cast.</def> <rj><au>Sir. P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The stockjobber thus from Change Alley goes down,⟦br⟧
And tips you, the freeman, a <qex>wink</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Winker</ent>⟦br⟧
